        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "We can even move this issue to the main neovim repo, I think.\n\nI've looked at this again, and I've abandoned the idea of the intermediate JSON for now.\n\nBasically we just need to duplicate `gen_one()` (because it may add content to the page, e.g. the Hugo frontmatter in HTML) and `visit_node()` (that's the one that actually turns a node into the output format).\n\nHere's my proposed incremental approach to add a `typ` output format to the current `gen_help_html.lua`\n\n### [DONE] Commit 1: Small refactor to separate the HTML-specific bits\n\n* Make gen() take an `output` param\n  * Update the website's `gendoc.lua` to use it\n* Rename `gen_one()` -> `gen_one_html()`\n* Rename `visit_node()` -> `ts_node_to_html()`\n* Add a mapping to gen() that calls the correct `gen_one*()` function.\n\nImplemented in https://github.com/neovim/neovim/commit/d0c7f870c29cdea5b13547f58b97983cfde9b345\nThe gendoc change is part of https://github.com/neovim/neovim.github.io/commit/6a0d2135758e91b13b357e5abfc169e08e5eaf12\n\nOptional: rename file to `export_help_docs.lua` and generally gen* to export* (the script doesn't generate the help - it converts its format).\nWe can bikeshed the naming a bit. Can also be done in its own commit after this one. \n\n### Commit 2: Simple version of Typst output\n\n* Add `gen_one_typ()` and `ts_node_to_typ()`\n  * I have a rough version at https://github.com/SqAtx/neovim/blob/gen_help_typ/src/gen/gen_help_html.lua that generates a passable usr_01.typ\n  * They should at least generate the user manual without errors\n\nIt's okay if the resulting PDF has visual problems\nIt's okay if the process is manual, like copy the user manual files -> run gen() -> merge all .typ files -> typst compile\n\nThe goal is to write enough Typst-specific Lua logic to be able to generate a version of the user manual, and be able to iterate on it without massive commits.\n\n### Commit 3: A readable user manual PDF\n\nFix formatting issues.\nMight take several commits, depending on the number and severity of issues.\nEnd goal: The user manual looks good. No formatting weirdness. Can be generated as a one-off for a specific version and distributed if we want to.\n\n### Commit 4: Automation\n\nThe user manual can be generated in one script call, and that script can be triggered by GHA.\nThen I can do this after every release, and maybe fix what got broken in that specific release.\nAt that point, we'll be in a good place.\n\n### Later: Nice to have\n\n* The manual gets generated automatically on release.\n  * I have a feeling it will require some tweaks so that version won't be good enough to e.g. be uploaded to the website. Maybe I can look at that version and fix things so that the PDF generated by x.1 is good\n* The reference manual can optionally get generated as well. Probably in the same PDF so that the links work.\n\n### When it comes up (no immediate plans)\n\n* Allow specifying different formats at the same time, so that we don't have to create the TS tree for each of them\n  * I don't think that's going to be a problem any time soon, so I'm okay with the small inefficiency for now\n\n",
